      <div type="corpus" source="#src-wikipedia">
        <head>Medusa: Myth and Representation</head>
        <p>In <placeName ref="#greece">Greek</placeName> mythology, <persName ref="#medusa">Medusa</persName> was one of the three <orgName ref="#gorgons">Gorgons</orgName>. Her sisters were <persName ref="#stheno">Stheno</persName> and <persName ref="#euryale">Euryale</persName>, and the three were commonly described as children of <persName ref="#phorcys">Phorcys</persName> and <persName ref="#ceto">Ceto</persName>. Unlike her immortal sisters, Medusa was mortal.</p>
        <p>Medusa is generally represented with living snakes in place of hair. Her gaze causes <rs ref="#petrification" type="concept">petrification</rs>. The hero <persName ref="#perseus">Perseus</persName> killed her while looking at her reflection in a polished shield. After the <rs ref="#beheading" type="event">beheading of Medusa</rs>, <persName ref="#pegasus">Pegasus</persName> and <persName ref="#chrysaor">Chrysaor</persName> emerged. Perseus later gave the head to <persName ref="#athena">Athena</persName>, who placed it on her aegis.</p>
        <p>Ancient traditions located the Gorgons in distant lands, including <placeName ref="#libya">Libya</placeName>. In classical antiquity, the image of the Gorgon's head became the <rs ref="#gorgoneion" type="concept">Gorgoneion</rs>, an image associated with <rs ref="#apotropaic" type="concept">apotropaic protection</rs>.</p>
        <p>A late and influential account appears in <bibl ref="#metamorphoses">Ovid's <title>Metamorphoses</title></bibl>. In this version, <persName ref="#poseidon">Neptune</persName> is associated with Medusa in the temple of <persName ref="#athena">Minerva</persName>, after which the goddess changes Medusa's admired hair into snakes. This <rs ref="#transformation" type="event">transformation</rs> shifts Medusa's representation from beautiful maiden to terrifying figure.</p>
        <p>Artistic representations emphasize different moments and meanings. <persName ref="#caravaggio">Caravaggio</persName>'s <rs ref="#caravaggio_medusa" type="artwork">Medusa</rs>, held by the <orgName ref="#uffizi">Uffizi Gallery</orgName> in <placeName ref="#florence">Florence</placeName>, presents the severed head on a shield. <persName ref="#rubens">Peter Paul Rubens</persName>'s <rs ref="#rubens_medusa" type="artwork">Head of Medusa</rs>, with animals attributed to <persName ref="#snyders">Frans Snyders</persName>, depicts the aftermath with snakes and blood; it is held by the <orgName ref="#khm">Kunsthistorisches Museum</orgName> in <placeName ref="#vienna">Vienna</placeName>. <persName ref="#cellini">Benvenuto Cellini</persName>'s <rs ref="#cellini_perseus" type="artwork">Perseus with the Head of Medusa</rs> presents the victorious hero and is installed at the <placeName ref="#loggia">Loggia dei Lanzi</placeName>.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="literaryEvidence" source="#src-ovid">
        <head>Ovidian Literary Evidence</head>
        <p>In Book IV, Perseus narrates how he viewed Medusa in a reflected bronze shield and struck her head from her neck. The passage connects her death with the birth of Pegasus and Chrysaor.</p>
        <quote source="#src-ovid">"the swift winged horse Pegasus and his brother the warrior Chrysaor, were born from their mother's blood."</quote>
        <p>Ovid then explains the snakes through a retrospective account of Medusa's beauty and Minerva's response, establishing a literary transformation that strongly shaped later visual culture.</p>
        <quote source="#src-ovid">"she changed the Gorgon's hair to foul snakes."</quote>
      </div>
